{{Infobox football biography | name = Antin Nanotaake | image = | fullname = Antin Nanotaake | birth_date = | birth_place = [[Kiribati]] | height = | position = [[Striker (association football)|Striker]] | clubnumber = 8<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/Competitions/TeamList/tabid/1014/Competition/b4ecf3e8-9c15-42b7-847a-ee2a0e7a6296/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=Kiribati Official Team List |work=oceaniafootball.com |publisher=Oceania Football Confederation |accessdate=25 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210135456/http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/Competitions/TeamList/tabid/1014/Competition/b4ecf3e8-9c15-42b7-847a-ee2a0e7a6296/language/en-US/Default.aspx |archivedate=10 February 2013 }}</ref> | youthyears1 = | youthclubs1 = | years1 = | clubs1 = | caps1 = | goals1 = | pcupdate = 25 May 2013 | nationalyears1 = 2011&ndash; | nationalteam1 = [[Kiribati national football team|Kiribati]] | nationalcaps1 = 4 | nationalgoals1 = 0 | ntupdate = 25 May 2013 }}
'''Antin Nanotaake''' is an [[Gilbertese language|I-Kiribati]] [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Striker (association football)|Striker]]. He represents Kiribati at [[Kiribati national football team|international level]].<ref name="NFT">{{cite web | url = http://www.national-football-teams.com/player/44774/Antin_Nanotaake.html| title = Antin Nanotaake| work= national-football-teams.com |publisher=National Football Teams| accessdate = 25 May 2013}}</ref>
==International career== Nanotaake made four appearances at the [[Men's Football at the 2011 Pacific Games|2011 Pacific Games]], in the 3-0 loss to [[Cook Islands national football team|Cook Islands]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/19a461c6-f66f-4e59-b45e-63a85c184b4f/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=Cook Islands 3-0 Kiribati |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=30 August 2011 |work=oceaniafootball.com |publisher=Oceania Football Confederation |accessdate=25 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210163951/http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/19a461c6-f66f-4e59-b45e-63a85c184b4f/language/en-US/Default.aspx |archivedate=10 February 2013 }}</ref> the 9-0 loss to [[Fiji national football team|Fiji]], where he was a substitute,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/9da7e00d-a5b0-4990-9f93-462f2a9238c5/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=Fiji 9 - 0 Kiribati |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=30 August 2011 |work=oceaniafootball.com |publisher=Oceania Football Confederation |accessdate=25 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210164136/http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/9da7e00d-a5b0-4990-9f93-462f2a9238c5/language/en-US/Default.aspx |archivedate=10 February 2013 }}</ref> and in the respective 1-17 losses to [[Tahiti national football team|Tahiti]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/b89f0e50-3f24-474e-a008-ad1dfa24757f/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=Kiribati 1 - 17 Tahiti |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=4 September 2011 |work=oceaniafootball.com |publisher=Oceania Football Confederation |accessdate=25 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210163625/http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/b89f0e50-3f24-474e-a008-ad1dfa24757f/language/en-US/Default.aspx |archivedate=10 February 2013 }}</ref> and [[Papua New Guinea national football team|Papua New Guinea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/22e56dd4-4204-47cf-9ce4-96d996c96142/language/en-US/Default.aspx |title=Kiribati 1 - 17 Papua New Guinea |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |date=3 September 2011 |work=oceaniafootball.com |publisher=Oceania Football Confederation |accessdate=25 May 2013 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210163731/http://www.oceaniafootball.com/ofc/News/ViewArticle/tabid/125/Article/22e56dd4-4204-47cf-9ce4-96d996c96142/language/en-US/Default.aspx |archivedate=10 February 2013 }}</ref>
==References== {{reflist}}
{{use dmy dates|date=May 2013}} {{DEFAULTSORT:Nanotaake, Antin}} [[Category:Association football forwards]] [[Category:I-Kiribati footballers]] [[Category:Kiribati international footballers]] [[Category:Living people]] [[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]
{{Kiribati-footy-bio-stub}}

The '''Asian Athletics Association''' is the continental governing body for the sport of [[athletics (sport)|athletics]] in [[Asia]]. It is headquartered in [[Singapore]]. It organises the [[Asian Championships in Athletics]] and other continental competitions.

The current president Qatari [[Dahlan Jumaan al-Hamad]], who was elected to the position in 2013.<ref>[http://www.gulf-times.com/sport/192/details/358067/dahlan-ousts-kalmadi-as-asian-athletics-chief Dahlan ousts Kalmadi as Asian athletics chief]. ''Gulf Times'' (2013-07-01). Retrieved on 2013-07-07.</ref> [[Suresh Kalmadi]] of [[India]] was the president from 2000 to 2013.<ref>[http://www.iaaf.org/mm/Document/News/GeneralNews/05/50/99/20091211124641_httppostedfile_NEWS108_17554.pdf IAAF Newsletter Edition 108] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023234954/http://www.iaaf.org/mm/Document/News/GeneralNews/05/50/99/20091211124641_httppostedfile_NEWS108_17554.pdf |date=October 23, 2012 }}. [[IAAF]] (2009-12-11). Retrieved on 2009-12-12.</ref>

