'''Richard Leigh''' (dates unknown) was an 18th-century [[English people|English]] businessman and [[cricket]] patron who ran his own [[R. Leigh's XI cricket team]] in nine [[first-class cricket|first-class]] matches 1793–95. His son, also [[Richard Leigh (cricketer)|Richard Leigh]], played first-class cricket in the 1800s but there is no record of Leigh senior having done so. Leigh, who resided at [[Wilmington, Kent|Wilmington]], near [[Dartford]], was an elected (1793) member of the [[Hambledon Club]] and an early member of [[Marylebone Cricket Club]] (MCC).<ref name=AC>Ashley-Cooper, p. 152.</ref> He was such a prominent match organiser in the 1790s that the [[Jane Gordon, Duchess of Gordon|Duchess of Gordon]] reportedly said to him: "Though I am the first, you are the second match-maker in England, Mr Leigh".<ref name=AC/>
