In [[chess]], a '''windmill''' is a [[chess tactics|tactic]] in which a combination of [[discovered attack|discovered checks]] and regular [[check (chess)|checks]], usually by a [[rook (chess)|rook]] and a [[bishop (chess)|bishop]], often forcing the opposing [[king (chess)|king]] to move back and forth between two squares, can win massive amounts of {{chessgloss|material}}. This tactic is also sometimes referred to as a ''see-saw''.<ref>[[David Hooper (chess player)|David Hooper]] and [[Kenneth Whyld]], ''[[The Oxford Companion to Chess]]'' (2nd ed. 1992), Oxford University Press, p. 363. {{ISBN|0-19-866164-9}}.</ref> {{algebraic notation|pos=toc}}
==Examples== {{Chess diagram |tright |Torre-Repetto vs. Lasker, Moscow 1925 |rd| | | |rd|nd|kd| |pd|bd| | | |pd|pd| | | | |pd|pd| | |pd | |qd| | | | |bl|ql | |pl| |pl| | | | | | | | |nl| |rl| |pl| | | | |pl|pl|pl | | | | |rl| |kl| |White played 25.Bf6!, sacrificing his queen in order to set up the windmill, and ended up ahead in material. }} In the game pictured at right,<ref>[http://www.chessgames.com/perl/chessgame?gid=1100063 Chessgames.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [[Carlos Torre Repetto|Carlos Torre-Repetto]] makes use of the windmill tactic against [[Emanuel Lasker]] to win two [[pawn (chess)|pawns]] and a bishop and enter into a winning [[chess endgame|endgame]] (although the bishop had to be given back). The move '''25. Bf6!''', {{chessgloss|hanging}} the [[queen (chess)|queen]], sets up the windmill. Black must accept the [[sacrifice (chess)|sacrifice]], as his own queen is unprotected, and any attempt to stop the windmill would simply give White the queen. Then '''25... Qxh5 26. Rxg7+ Kh8 27. Rxf7+''' discovered check by the bishop. White simply repeats the regular check/discovered check pattern, taking as many pieces as he can with his rook. '''27... Kg8 28. Rg7+ Kh8 29. Rxb7+ Kg8 30. Rg7+ Kh8 31. Rg5+ Kh7 32. Rxh5''' White concludes the windmill by taking the black queen.
Another example is in [[Bobby Fischer]]'s [[The Game of the Century (chess)|Game of the Century]], from moves 18 to 23. In this case, the windmill involved a [[knight (chess)|knight]] and a bishop. {{clear}}
